\section{Differences between D1 and SQLite}{

D1 \emph{is} SQLite, but reached over Cloudflare's HTTP API rather than a local
file. This shapes how RD1 behaves compared with a file-based driver such as
RSQLite:
\itemize{
\item \strong{No persistent connection.} A \code{D1Connection} only bundles the database
ID and credentials. \code{\link[DBI:dbDisconnect]{DBI::dbDisconnect()}} is a no-op that marks the
connection invalid; there is no socket to close.
\item \strong{No transactions.} Each statement is sent and committed on its own.
\code{dbBegin()}/\code{dbCommit()}/\code{dbRollback()} are not supported. Atomic restores
are instead available through time travel (see below).
\item \strong{Eager results.} D1 returns a query's full result in one response, so
results are materialised in memory and \code{\link[DBI:dbFetch]{DBI::dbFetch()}} simply pages
through them locally.
\item \strong{Storage classes versus JSON.} Results arrive as JSON, which cannot
distinguish SQLite storage classes for whole numbers (a \code{REAL} \code{6.0} and an
\code{INTEGER} \code{6} both serialise as \code{6}). For ad-hoc queries RD1 infers types
from the values (whole numbers become integer, otherwise double). For
\code{\link[DBI:dbReadTable]{DBI::dbReadTable()}} it reads the declared column types with
\verb{PRAGMA table_info()} and coerces columns to exactly what RSQLite would
return, so whole tables round-trip faithfully.
\item \strong{No 64-bit integer tuning.} There is no \code{bigint} connection argument;
integers beyond double precision may lose precision.
\item \strong{Booleans, dates, and times.} As in SQLite, these have no native type.
Like RSQLite, logical maps to \code{INTEGER} and \code{Date}/\code{POSIXct}/\code{difftime}
map to \code{REAL} on write, and are read back as integer/numeric rather than
reconstructed.
\item \strong{Bound-parameter limit.} D1 caps bound parameters per request, so
\code{\link[DBI:dbWriteTable]{DBI::dbWriteTable()}} inserts rows in chunks.
\item \strong{Hidden internal tables.} \code{\link[DBI:dbListTables]{DBI::dbListTables()}} omits D1/SQLite internal
tables (\verb{sqlite_*}, \verb{_cf_*}).
\item \strong{Capabilities SQLite lacks.} Time travel and bookmarks
(\code{\link[=d1_bookmark]{d1_bookmark()}}, \code{\link[=d1_restore]{d1_restore()}}), HTTP export/import
(\code{\link[=d1_export]{d1_export()}}, \code{\link[=d1_import]{d1_import()}}), database management, and read replication.
}
